{"key":"processedPost-12448894","value":{"id":12448894,"first":12447117,"last":12448894,"when":1272130877,"utime":"04/24/10 08:41 PM","content":"First of all, don't use aluminum.&nbsp; The mycelium will eat through it prior to first flush, leading to bottom pinning due to the fresh air entering through the holes the mycelium has digested through the metal.<br /><br />Second, the casing layer goes on top, not top and bottom, despite horrible so-called 'teks' to the contrary.<br /><br />If you want to case grains, sprinkle the colonized grains into a plastic tray, and cover with 1/2\" of 50/50 casing material.&nbsp; When the casing layer is partially colonized, introduce to fruiting conditions.&nbsp; For more information, do a search on 'patching'.<br /><br />A better bet for higher yield is to spawn the colonized grains into a bulk substrate material such as compost or manure.&nbsp; When colonized, introduce to fruiting conditions uncased.<br />RR","title":"Re: Just to clarify","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}